context: The contemporary Liberal Party generally advocates economic liberalism (see <a0_0><b4_0>New Right<b4_0/><a0_0/>). Historically, the party has supported a higher degree of <b8_0>economic protectionism and interventionism<b8_0/> than it has in recent decades. However, from its foundation the party has identified itself as <a1_0><b5_0>anti-socialist<b5_0/><a1_0/>. Strong opposition to socialism and communism in Australia and abroad was one of its founding principles. The party's founder and longest-serving leader <a2_0><a3_0><b6_0><b7_0>Robert Menzies<b7_0/><b6_0/><a3_0/><a2_0/> envisaged that Australia's middle class would form its main constituency.
